The system should stubbornly refuse to lose work from a polecat.

## Current Problem

- gt spawn --force bypasses safety checks
- gt shutdown doesn't check for uncommitted work
- Witness cleanup doesn't check git status

## Desired Behavior

Before any polecat cleanup, check:
1. git status - any uncommitted changes?
2. git stash list - any stashes?
3. Unpushed commits on branch?
4. Unsynced beads changes?

If ANY of these exist:
- REFUSE to clean up
- Print clear error message listing what would be lost
- Require explicit --nuclear flag to force (not just --force)

## Implementation

Add to cleanupPolecat() in witness/manager.go:
```go
func (m *Manager) checkUncommittedWork(polecatName string) error {
    dir := m.polecatDir(polecatName)

    // Check git status
    if hasUncommitted, _ := git.HasUncommittedChanges(dir); hasUncommitted {
        return fmt.Errorf("polecat %s has uncommitted changes", polecatName)
    }

    // Check stashes
    if stashCount, _ := git.StashCount(dir); stashCount > 0 {
        return fmt.Errorf("polecat %s has %d stashes", polecatName, stashCount)
    }

    // Check unpushed commits
    if unpushed, _ := git.UnpushedCommits(dir); unpushed > 0 {
        return fmt.Errorf("polecat %s has %d unpushed commits", polecatName, unpushed)
    }

    return nil
}
```

## Affected Commands

- gt shutdown
- gt rig shutdown
- Witness cleanup
- gt spawn --force (should warn if overwriting)

## Overview

Implement persistent HTTP/2 connections to keep Cloud Run containers warm.

## Problem

Cloud Run has cold start latency when scaling from 0. Persistent connections keep containers warm.

## Implementation

```go
type PersistentConnectionManager struct {
    serviceURL string
    conn       net.Conn
    client     *http2.ClientConn
    mu         sync.Mutex
    lastUsed   time.Time
    keepAlive  time.Duration
}

func (m *PersistentConnectionManager) GetConnection() (*http2.ClientConn, error) {
    m.mu.Lock()
    defer m.mu.Unlock()

    // Reuse existing connection if healthy
    if m.client != nil && m.client.CanTakeNewRequest() {
        m.lastUsed = time.Now()
        return m.client, nil
    }

    // Create new connection
    return m.dial()
}

func (m *PersistentConnectionManager) keepAliveLoop() {
    ticker := time.NewTicker(m.keepAlive / 2)
    for range ticker.C {
        m.mu.Lock()
        if time.Since(m.lastUsed) > m.keepAlive {
            // Connection idle too long, close it
            m.close()
        } else {
            // Send ping to keep alive
            m.ping()
        }
        m.mu.Unlock()
    }
}
```

